INSERT INTO questions (subject, topic, difficulty, question_text, choices, correct_answer, explanation, exam_type) VALUES
('General Education','Science','easy','The basic unit of life is the:','[{"key":"A","text":"tissue"},{"key":"B","text":"organ"},{"key":"C","text":"cell"},{"key":"D","text":"molecule"}]','C','The cell is the smallest unit of life capable of performing all basic life functions.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which organelle is known as the "powerhouse of the cell"?','[{"key":"A","text":"Nucleus"},{"key":"B","text":"Ribosome"},{"key":"C","text":"Mitochondria"},{"key":"D","text":"Golgi apparatus"}]','C','Mitochondria produce ATP (adenosine triphosphate) through cellular respiration, providing energy for the cell.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which process do plants use to make food using sunlight?','[{"key":"A","text":"Cellular respiration"},{"key":"B","text":"Fermentation"},{"key":"C","text":"Photosynthesis"},{"key":"D","text":"Transpiration"}]','C','Photosynthesis converts light energy, carbon dioxide, and water into glucose and oxygen.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','The overall equation for photosynthesis is:','[{"key":"A","text":"C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + ATP"},{"key":"B","text":"6CO₂ + 6H₂O + light → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂"},{"key":"C","text":"6O₂ + C₆H₁₂O₆ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O"},{"key":"D","text":"CO₂ + H₂O → CH₂O + O"}]','B','Photosynthesis: 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + light energy → C₆H₁₂O₆ (glucose) + 6O₂.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','DNA is located in the _____ of the cell.','[{"key":"A","text":"cytoplasm"},{"key":"B","text":"cell membrane"},{"key":"C","text":"ribosome"},{"key":"D","text":"nucleus"}]','D','The nucleus contains the cell''s DNA (genetic material) and controls cell activities.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which type of cell division produces gametes (sex cells)?','[{"key":"A","text":"Mitosis"},{"key":"B","text":"Binary fission"},{"key":"C","text":"Meiosis"},{"key":"D","text":"Cytokinesis"}]','C','Meiosis produces haploid gametes (sperm and egg cells) with half the chromosome number of the parent cell.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','In genetics, the observable trait of an organism is called its:','[{"key":"A","text":"genotype"},{"key":"B","text":"phenotype"},{"key":"C","text":"allele"},{"key":"D","text":"chromosome"}]','B','The phenotype is the observable physical expression of an organism''s genes (e.g., eye color, height).','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','What is the term for organisms that break down dead organic matter?','[{"key":"A","text":"Producers"},{"key":"B","text":"Consumers"},{"key":"C","text":"Decomposers"},{"key":"D","text":"Predators"}]','C','Decomposers (e.g., fungi, bacteria) break down dead organisms, recycling nutrients back into the ecosystem.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Gregor Mendel''s experiments with pea plants established the law of:','[{"key":"A","text":"Natural selection"},{"key":"B","text":"Segregation and independent assortment"},{"key":"C","text":"Conservation of energy"},{"key":"D","text":"Cell theory"}]','B','Mendel''s laws: Law of Segregation (alleles separate during gamete formation) and Law of Independent Assortment (genes on different chromosomes sort independently).','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which blood type is the universal donor?','[{"key":"A","text":"Type A"},{"key":"B","text":"Type B"},{"key":"C","text":"Type AB"},{"key":"D","text":"Type O"}]','D','Type O negative blood lacks A, B, and Rh antigens, making it compatible with all blood types.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','If a mother is blood type A (heterozygous, AO) and the father is blood type B (heterozygous, BO), what blood types are possible in their children?','[{"key":"A","text":"A and B only"},{"key":"B","text":"A, B, AB, and O"},{"key":"C","text":"O only"},{"key":"D","text":"AB only"}]','B','Cross AO × BO gives: AA (type A), AO (type A), BO (type B), AB (type AB), OO (type O) — all four types are possible.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','The process by which plants lose water through their leaves is called:','[{"key":"A","text":"osmosis"},{"key":"B","text":"photosynthesis"},{"key":"C","text":"transpiration"},{"key":"D","text":"respiration"}]','C','Transpiration is the process by which water is evaporated from the aerial parts of plants, especially leaves.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which organ system is responsible for transporting nutrients and oxygen throughout the body?','[{"key":"A","text":"Digestive system"},{"key":"B","text":"Nervous system"},{"key":"C","text":"Circulatory system"},{"key":"D","text":"Respiratory system"}]','C','The circulatory system (heart, blood vessels, blood) transports oxygen, nutrients, hormones, and waste products throughout the body.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','What gas do animals exhale as a waste product of cellular respiration?','[{"key":"A","text":"Oxygen"},{"key":"B","text":"Nitrogen"},{"key":"C","text":"Carbon dioxide"},{"key":"D","text":"Hydrogen"}]','C','Cellular respiration breaks down glucose: C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + ATP. CO₂ is exhaled as waste.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which level of biological organization comes between organ and organism?','[{"key":"A","text":"Tissue"},{"key":"B","text":"Cell"},{"key":"C","text":"Organ system"},{"key":"D","text":"Population"}]','C','The correct sequence is: cell → tissue → organ → organ system → organism.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','hard','A plant cell is placed in a hypertonic solution. What happens?','[{"key":"A","text":"The cell swells and may burst"},{"key":"B","text":"The cell loses water and the membrane pulls away from the cell wall (plasmolysis)"},{"key":"C","text":"Nothing changes"},{"key":"D","text":"The cell gains water and becomes turgid"}]','B','In a hypertonic solution (higher solute concentration outside), water moves out of the cell by osmosis, causing plasmolysis in plant cells.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','What is the function of the ribosome?','[{"key":"A","text":"DNA replication"},{"key":"B","text":"Protein synthesis"},{"key":"C","text":"Energy production"},{"key":"D","text":"Lipid storage"}]','B','Ribosomes are the site of protein synthesis, translating mRNA sequences into amino acid chains.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Dominant and recessive alleles are represented as:','[{"key":"A","text":"Capital letter for recessive, lowercase for dominant"},{"key":"B","text":"Capital letter for dominant, lowercase for recessive"},{"key":"C","text":"Both written in capital letters"},{"key":"D","text":"Both written in lowercase"}]','B','By convention, dominant alleles are represented by capital letters (e.g., T) and recessive alleles by lowercase (e.g., t).','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which kingdom includes mushrooms and molds?','[{"key":"A","text":"Plantae"},{"key":"B","text":"Animalia"},{"key":"C","text":"Fungi"},{"key":"D","text":"Protista"}]','C','Fungi are eukaryotic organisms that obtain nutrients through absorption. Mushrooms, molds, and yeasts belong to Kingdom Fungi.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','The ENSO (El Niño-Southern Oscillation) causes:','[{"key":"A","text":"Increased rainfall in the Philippines during El Niño"},{"key":"B","text":"Drought and reduced rainfall in the Philippines during El Niño"},{"key":"C","text":"Colder temperatures globally"},{"key":"D","text":"Stronger typhoons in the Pacific during El Niño"}]','B','During El Niño, warmer Pacific waters shift eastward, typically causing drought and reduced rainfall in the Philippines.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','hard','Which of the following correctly describes the function of the Golgi apparatus?','[{"key":"A","text":"Site of photosynthesis"},{"key":"B","text":"Produces energy via ATP synthesis"},{"key":"C","text":"Modifies, packages, and ships proteins made by ribosomes"},{"key":"D","text":"Contains genetic information"}]','C','The Golgi apparatus processes and packages proteins and lipids from the ER for secretion or use within the cell.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','In a food chain, energy transfer between trophic levels is approximately:','[{"key":"A","text":"90%"},{"key":"B","text":"50%"},{"key":"C","text":"10%"},{"key":"D","text":"1%"}]','C','The 10% law states that only about 10% of energy is transferred from one trophic level to the next; the rest is lost as heat.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which system includes the brain and spinal cord?','[{"key":"A","text":"Endocrine system"},{"key":"B","text":"Central nervous system"},{"key":"C","text":"Peripheral nervous system"},{"key":"D","text":"Immune system"}]','B','The central nervous system (CNS) consists of the brain and spinal cord. The peripheral nervous system connects the CNS to the rest of the body.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Darwin''s theory of evolution is based on:','[{"key":"A","text":"Inheritance of acquired characteristics"},{"key":"B","text":"Natural selection — survival of the fittest"},{"key":"C","text":"Spontaneous generation of new species"},{"key":"D","text":"Random mutation without selection"}]','B','Darwin proposed that organisms with favorable traits survive and reproduce more (natural selection), leading to evolution over generations.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which of the following is a characteristic of living things?','[{"key":"A","text":"Made of only one element"},{"key":"B","text":"Cannot respond to stimuli"},{"key":"C","text":"Can reproduce"},{"key":"D","text":"Do not require energy"}]','C','All living things share characteristics: reproduction, metabolism, growth, response to stimuli, homeostasis, and cellular organization.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','What is the difference between mitosis and meiosis?','[{"key":"A","text":"Mitosis produces 4 daughter cells; meiosis produces 2"},{"key":"B","text":"Mitosis produces genetically identical diploid cells; meiosis produces genetically varied haploid cells"},{"key":"C","text":"Mitosis occurs only in sex organs; meiosis occurs everywhere"},{"key":"D","text":"Mitosis reduces chromosome number; meiosis maintains it"}]','B','Mitosis → 2 identical diploid cells (for growth/repair). Meiosis → 4 genetically varied haploid cells (gametes).','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','The heart has how many chambers?','[{"key":"A","text":"2"},{"key":"B","text":"3"},{"key":"C","text":"4"},{"key":"D","text":"5"}]','C','The human heart has 4 chambers: right atrium, right ventricle, left atrium, and left ventricle.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','hard','In protein synthesis, which type of RNA carries amino acids to the ribosome?','[{"key":"A","text":"mRNA"},{"key":"B","text":"rRNA"},{"key":"C","text":"tRNA"},{"key":"D","text":"snRNA"}]','C','Transfer RNA (tRNA) carries specific amino acids to the ribosome, matching its anticodon to the mRNA codon during translation.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which phase of mitosis is characterized by chromosomes aligning at the cell''s equator?','[{"key":"A","text":"Prophase"},{"key":"B","text":"Metaphase"},{"key":"C","text":"Anaphase"},{"key":"D","text":"Telophase"}]','B','During metaphase, chromosomes line up at the metaphase plate (cell''s equator) before being pulled to opposite poles.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which gas makes up approximately 78% of Earth''s atmosphere?','[{"key":"A","text":"Oxygen"},{"key":"B","text":"Carbon dioxide"},{"key":"C","text":"Argon"},{"key":"D","text":"Nitrogen"}]','D','Earth''s atmosphere: approximately 78% nitrogen, 21% oxygen, 1% argon, and 0.04% carbon dioxide.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','A homozygous tall plant (TT) is crossed with a homozygous short plant (tt). All offspring are:','[{"key":"A","text":"tt (short)"},{"key":"B","text":"TT (tall)"},{"key":"C","text":"Tt (tall)"},{"key":"D","text":"50% tall, 50% short"}]','C','TT × tt produces all Tt offspring. Since T (tall) is dominant, all F1 offspring are tall with genotype Tt.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','What is the term for the variety of species in an ecosystem?','[{"key":"A","text":"Biomass"},{"key":"B","text":"Biodiversity"},{"key":"C","text":"Niche"},{"key":"D","text":"Habitat"}]','B','Biodiversity refers to the variety of life forms in a given area, including genetic diversity, species diversity, and ecosystem diversity.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which type of symbiosis benefits both organisms?','[{"key":"A","text":"Parasitism"},{"key":"B","text":"Commensalism"},{"key":"C","text":"Mutualism"},{"key":"D","text":"Competition"}]','C','Mutualism is a symbiotic relationship where both organisms benefit (e.g., bees and flowers — bees get nectar, flowers get pollinated).','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','hard','Which of the following provides evidence for evolution?','[{"key":"A","text":"Vestigial structures, fossil record, molecular homology, and comparative anatomy"},{"key":"B","text":"Spontaneous generation of new organisms"},{"key":"C","text":"The constant number of species on Earth"},{"key":"D","text":"Inheritance of traits acquired during an organism''s lifetime"}]','A','Evidence for evolution includes: fossil record, homologous structures, vestigial structures, DNA/molecular similarities, and direct observation of natural selection.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','What is the role of the cell membrane?','[{"key":"A","text":"Produce proteins"},{"key":"B","text":"Store genetic information"},{"key":"C","text":"Regulate what enters and exits the cell"},{"key":"D","text":"Generate energy"}]','C','The cell membrane (phospholipid bilayer) is selectively permeable — it controls the movement of substances in and out of the cell.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','An organism that makes its own food using sunlight is called a/an:','[{"key":"A","text":"heterotroph"},{"key":"B","text":"autotroph"},{"key":"C","text":"consumer"},{"key":"D","text":"parasite"}]','B','Autotrophs (producers) make their own food via photosynthesis or chemosynthesis. Plants, algae, and cyanobacteria are autotrophs.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','What is the term for the specific location in an ecosystem where an organism lives?','[{"key":"A","text":"Niche"},{"key":"B","text":"Ecosystem"},{"key":"C","text":"Habitat"},{"key":"D","text":"Biome"}]','C','A habitat is the physical environment where an organism lives. A niche is the role an organism plays in its ecosystem.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','hard','Which nitrogenous base pairs with adenine in DNA?','[{"key":"A","text":"Guanine"},{"key":"B","text":"Cytosine"},{"key":"C","text":"Uracil"},{"key":"D","text":"Thymine"}]','D','In DNA: Adenine pairs with Thymine (A-T) and Cytosine pairs with Guanine (C-G) via complementary base pairing.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','The human digestive system breaks food down into:','[{"key":"A","text":"Whole food particles for absorption"},{"key":"B","text":"Nutrients small enough for absorption into the blood"},{"key":"C","text":"Waste products only"},{"key":"D","text":"Energy only"}]','B','Digestion mechanically and chemically breaks down food into small molecules (glucose, amino acids, fatty acids) that can be absorbed into the bloodstream.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which hormone regulates blood glucose levels?','[{"key":"A","text":"Adrenaline"},{"key":"B","text":"Estrogen"},{"key":"C","text":"Insulin"},{"key":"D","text":"Thyroxine"}]','C','Insulin (produced by the pancreas) lowers blood glucose by allowing cells to absorb and use glucose. Glucagon raises blood glucose.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','What is the process of water moving through a semi-permeable membrane from low to high solute concentration?','[{"key":"A","text":"Diffusion"},{"key":"B","text":"Active transport"},{"key":"C","text":"Osmosis"},{"key":"D","text":"Filtration"}]','C','Osmosis is the passive movement of water across a semi-permeable membrane from an area of low solute concentration to high solute concentration.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which type of muscle is found in the heart?','[{"key":"A","text":"Smooth muscle"},{"key":"B","text":"Skeletal muscle"},{"key":"C","text":"Cardiac muscle"},{"key":"D","text":"Voluntary muscle"}]','C','Cardiac muscle is found exclusively in the heart. It is involuntary, striated, and able to contract rhythmically without fatigue.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','hard','A cross between a white-flowered and red-flowered snapdragon produces pink flowers (incomplete dominance). If two pink-flowered plants are crossed, the expected phenotypic ratio is:','[{"key":"A","text":"All pink"},{"key":"B","text":"3 red : 1 white"},{"key":"C","text":"1 red : 2 pink : 1 white"},{"key":"D","text":"1 red : 1 pink"}]','C','Rr × Rr (where R = red, r = white): RR (red) : Rr (pink) : rr (white) = 1:2:1 phenotypic ratio in incomplete dominance.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','What is the role of white blood cells?','[{"key":"A","text":"Carry oxygen"},{"key":"B","text":"Transport nutrients"},{"key":"C","text":"Fight infection and foreign substances"},{"key":"D","text":"Form blood clots"}]','C','White blood cells (leukocytes) are part of the immune system; they defend the body against bacteria, viruses, and other pathogens.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which of the following is NOT a function of the skeletal system?','[{"key":"A","text":"Support and movement"},{"key":"B","text":"Protection of organs"},{"key":"C","text":"Pumping blood"},{"key":"D","text":"Blood cell production"}]','C','The skeletal system provides support, protection, movement (via joints), and produces blood cells in bone marrow. Pumping blood is the heart''s function.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','What is the term for the movement of substances from high to low concentration without energy?','[{"key":"A","text":"Active transport"},{"key":"B","text":"Endocytosis"},{"key":"C","text":"Facilitated diffusion"},{"key":"D","text":"Passive diffusion"}]','D','Passive diffusion (or simple diffusion) is the movement of molecules from areas of high to low concentration without energy expenditure.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','easy','Which layer of the skin provides insulation and stores energy?','[{"key":"A","text":"Epidermis"},{"key":"B","text":"Dermis"},{"key":"C","text":"Hypodermis (subcutaneous layer)"},{"key":"D","text":"Stratum corneum"}]','C','The hypodermis (subcutaneous fat layer) provides insulation, cushioning, and energy storage.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','The theory that proposes that species change over long periods of time due to natural selection is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Cell theory"},{"key":"B","text":"Germ theory"},{"key":"C","text":"Theory of evolution"},{"key":"D","text":"Big Bang theory"}]','C','Darwin''s theory of evolution by natural selection explains how species change over time through differential reproductive success.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','hard','Which of the following is an example of a vestigial structure in humans?','[{"key":"A","text":"Femur"},{"key":"B","text":"Appendix"},{"key":"C","text":"Heart"},{"key":"D","text":"Cornea"}]','B','The appendix is considered a vestigial structure — a remnant of an organ that was functional in human ancestors but has no essential function today.','secondary'),
('General Education','Science','medium','Which macromolecule serves as the primary energy storage molecule in plants?','[{"key":"A","text":"Protein"},{"key":"B","text":"Starch"},{"key":"C","text":"DNA"},{"key":"D","text":"Lipid"}]','B','Plants store excess glucose as starch (a polysaccharide). Animals store it as glycogen; lipids are long-term energy storage.','secondary');
